&lt;p&gt;If it&amp;rsquo;s not installed, execute the following commands:&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Monitor NVIDIA Components</title><link>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/ninja-workshops/14-cisco-ai-pods/2-workshop/4-monitor-nvidia-components/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/ninja-workshops/14-cisco-ai-pods/2-workshop/4-monitor-nvidia-components/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;In this section, we&amp;rsquo;ll use the Prometheus &lt;strong&gt;receiver&lt;/strong&gt; with the OpenTelemetry collector
to monitor the NVIDIA components running in the OpenShift cluster. We&amp;rsquo;ll start by
navigating to the directory where the collector configuration file is stored:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code-block"&gt;
 &lt;div class="code-block__header"&gt;
 &lt;span class="code-block__file"&gt;&lt;span class="code-block__lang"&gt;bash&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;button class="code-block__copy" type="button" aria-label="Copy code to clipboard"&gt;Copy&lt;/button&gt;
 &lt;/div&gt;
 &lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"&gt;&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash"&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="nb"&gt;cd&lt;/span&gt; otel-collector&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;h2 id="capture-the-nvidia-dcgm-exporter-metrics"&gt;
 &lt;span class="heading-text"&gt;Capture the NVIDIA DCGM Exporter metrics&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;a class="heading-anchor" href="#capture-the-nvidia-dcgm-exporter-metrics" aria-label="Permalink" aria-hidden="true"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;a href="https://github.com/NVIDIA/dcgm-exporter" target="_blank" rel="noopener"&gt;NVIDIA DCGM exporter &lt;span aria-hidden="true" style="font-size:0.75em;opacity:0.6;"&gt;&amp;#x2197;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
 is running
in our OpenShift cluster. It exposes GPU metrics that we can send to Splunk.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Monitor the Vector Database</title><link>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/ninja-workshops/14-cisco-ai-pods/2-workshop/5-monitor-vector-db/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/ninja-workshops/14-cisco-ai-pods/2-workshop/5-monitor-vector-db/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;In this step, we&amp;rsquo;ll configure the Prometheus receiver to monitor the Weaviate vector database.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="what-is-a-vector-database"&gt;
 &lt;span class="heading-text"&gt;What is a Vector Database?&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;a class="heading-anchor" href="#what-is-a-vector-database" aria-label="Permalink" aria-hidden="true"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;vector database&lt;/strong&gt; stores and indexes data as numerical &amp;ldquo;vector embeddings,&amp;rdquo; which capture
the &lt;strong&gt;semantic meaning&lt;/strong&gt; of information like text or images. Unlike traditional databases,
they excel at &lt;strong&gt;similarity searches&lt;/strong&gt;, finding conceptually related data points rather
than exact matches.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="how-is-a-vector-database-used"&gt;
 &lt;span class="heading-text"&gt;How is a Vector Database Used?&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;a class="heading-anchor" href="#how-is-a-vector-database-used" aria-label="Permalink" aria-hidden="true"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Vector databases play a key role in a pattern called
&lt;strong&gt;Retrieval Augmented Generation (RAG)&lt;/strong&gt;, which is widely used by
applications that leverage Large Language Models (LLMs).&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Monitor Storage</title><link>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/ninja-workshops/14-cisco-ai-pods/2-workshop/6-monitor-storage/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/ninja-workshops/14-cisco-ai-pods/2-workshop/6-monitor-storage/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;In this step, we&amp;rsquo;ll configure the Prometheus receiver to monitor the storage.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="what-storage-do-cisco-ai-pods-utilize"&gt;
 &lt;span class="heading-text"&gt;What storage do Cisco AI PODs utilize?&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;a class="heading-anchor" href="#what-storage-do-cisco-ai-pods-utilize" aria-label="Permalink" aria-hidden="true"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Cisco AI PODs have a number of different storage options, including Pure Storage,
VAST, and NetApp.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The workshop will focus on Pure Storage.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="how-do-we-capture-pure-storage-metrics"&gt;
 &lt;span class="heading-text"&gt;How do we capture Pure Storage metrics?&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;a class="heading-anchor" href="#how-do-we-capture-pure-storage-metrics" aria-label="Permalink" aria-hidden="true"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Cisco AI PODs that utilize Pure Storage also use a technology called Portworx,
which provides persistent storage for Kubernetes.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Review AI POD Dashboards</title><link>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/ninja-workshops/14-cisco-ai-pods/2-workshop/7-review-ai-pod-dashboards/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/ninja-workshops/14-cisco-ai-pods/2-workshop/7-review-ai-pod-dashboards/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;In this section, we&amp;rsquo;ll review the AI POD dashboards in Splunk Observability Cloud
to confirm that the data from NVIDIA, Pure Storage, and Weaviate is captured
as expected.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="update-the-opentelemetry-collector-config"&gt;
 &lt;span class="heading-text"&gt;Update the OpenTelemetry Collector Config&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;a class="heading-anchor" href="#update-the-opentelemetry-collector-config" aria-label="Permalink" aria-hidden="true"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We can apply the collector configuration changes by running the following Helm command:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code-block"&gt;
 &lt;div class="code-block__header"&gt;
 &lt;span class="code-block__file"&gt;&lt;span class="code-block__lang"&gt;bash&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;button class="code-block__copy" type="button" aria-label="Copy code to clipboard"&gt;Copy&lt;/button&gt;
 &lt;/div&gt;
 &lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"&gt;&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash"&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;{&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt; -z &lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nv"&gt;$CLUSTER_NAME&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;]&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;||&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="se"&gt;\
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt; -z &lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nv"&gt;$ENVIRONMENT_NAME&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;]&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;||&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="se"&gt;\
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt; -z &lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nv"&gt;$USER_NAME&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;}&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;&amp;amp;&amp;amp;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="se"&gt;\
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; &lt;span class="nb"&gt;echo&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;Error: Missing variables&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;||&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="se"&gt;\
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; helm upgrade splunk-otel-collector &lt;span class="se"&gt;\
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; --set&lt;span class="o"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;clusterName=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nv"&gt;$CLUSTER_NAME&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="se"&gt;\
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; --set&lt;span class="o"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;environment=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nv"&gt;$ENVIRONMENT_NAME&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="se"&gt;\
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; --set&lt;span class="o"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;splunkObservability.accessToken=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nv"&gt;$ACCESS_TOKEN&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="se"&gt;\
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; --set&lt;span class="o"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;splunkObservability.realm=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nv"&gt;$REALM&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="se"&gt;\
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; --set&lt;span class="o"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;splunkPlatform.endpoint=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nv"&gt;$HEC_URL&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="se"&gt;\
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; --set&lt;span class="o"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;splunkPlatform.token=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nv"&gt;$HEC_TOKEN&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="se"&gt;\
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; --set&lt;span class="o"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;splunkPlatform.index=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="nv"&gt;$SPLUNK_INDEX&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="s2"&gt;&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="se"&gt;\
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; -f ./otel-collector-values.yaml &lt;span class="se"&gt;\
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; -n &lt;span class="nv"&gt;$USER_NAME&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="se"&gt;\
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt; splunk-otel-collector-chart/splunk-otel-collector&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;Note: if you get an error that says &lt;code&gt;Missing variables&lt;/code&gt;, you&amp;rsquo;ll need to
define your environment variables again. Add your participant number
before running the following commands:&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Review the LLM Application</title><link>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/ninja-workshops/14-cisco-ai-pods/2-workshop/8-review-llm-app/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/ninja-workshops/14-cisco-ai-pods/2-workshop/8-review-llm-app/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;In the final step of the workshop, we&amp;rsquo;ll deploy an application to our OpenShift cluster
that uses the instruct and embeddings models.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="what-is-langchain"&gt;
 &lt;span class="heading-text"&gt;What is LangChain?&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;a class="heading-anchor" href="#what-is-langchain" aria-label="Permalink" aria-hidden="true"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Like most applications that interact with LLMs, our application is written in Python.
It also uses &lt;a href="https://www.langchain.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"&gt;LangChain &lt;span aria-hidden="true" style="font-size:0.75em;opacity:0.6;"&gt;&amp;#x2197;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
, which is an open-source orchestration
framework that simplifies the development of applications powered by LLMs.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="application-overview"&gt;
 &lt;span class="heading-text"&gt;Application Overview&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;a class="heading-anchor" href="#application-overview" aria-label="Permalink" aria-hidden="true"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h3 id="connect-to-the-llms"&gt;
 &lt;span class="heading-text"&gt;Connect to the LLMs&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;a class="heading-anchor" href="#connect-to-the-llms" aria-label="Permalink" aria-hidden="true"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Our application starts by connecting to two LLMs that we&amp;rsquo;ll be using:&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Instrument the LLM Application</title><link>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/ninja-workshops/14-cisco-ai-pods/2-workshop/9-instrument-llm-app/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/ninja-workshops/14-cisco-ai-pods/2-workshop/9-instrument-llm-app/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="instrument-the-application-with-opentelemetry"&gt;
 &lt;span class="heading-text"&gt;Instrument the Application with OpenTelemetry&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;a class="heading-anchor" href="#instrument-the-application-with-opentelemetry" aria-label="Permalink" aria-hidden="true"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h3 id="instrumentation-packages"&gt;
 &lt;span class="heading-text"&gt;Instrumentation Packages&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;a class="heading-anchor" href="#instrumentation-packages" aria-label="Permalink" aria-hidden="true"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To capture metrics, traces, and logs from our application, we&amp;rsquo;ve instrumented it with OpenTelemetry.
This required adding the following package to the &lt;code&gt;requirements.txt&lt;/code&gt; file (which ultimately gets
installed with &lt;code&gt;pip install&lt;/code&gt;):&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code-block"&gt;
 &lt;div class="code-block__header"&gt;
 &lt;span class="code-block__file"&gt;&lt;span class="code-block__lang"&gt;text&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;button class="code-block__copy" type="button" aria-label="Copy code to clipboard"&gt;Copy&lt;/button&gt;
 &lt;/div&gt;
 &lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"&gt;&lt;code class="language-text" data-lang="text"&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;splunk-opentelemetry==2.8.0&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We also added the following to the &lt;code&gt;Dockerfile&lt;/code&gt; used to build the
container image for this application, to install additional OpenTelemetry
instrumentation packages:&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Deploy the LLM Application</title><link>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/ninja-workshops/14-cisco-ai-pods/2-workshop/10-deploy-llm-app/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/ninja-workshops/14-cisco-ai-pods/2-workshop/10-deploy-llm-app/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="deploy-the-llm-application"&gt;
 &lt;span class="heading-text"&gt;Deploy the LLM Application&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;a class="heading-anchor" href="#deploy-the-llm-application" aria-label="Permalink" aria-hidden="true"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Use the following command to deploy this application to the OpenShift cluster:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code-block"&gt;
 &lt;div class="code-block__header"&gt;
 &lt;span class="code-block__file"&gt;&lt;span class="code-block__lang"&gt;bash&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;button class="code-block__copy" type="button" aria-label="Copy code to clipboard"&gt;Copy&lt;/button&gt;
 &lt;/div&gt;
 &lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"&gt;&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash"&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="nb"&gt;cd&lt;/span&gt; ~/workshop/cisco-ai-pods
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;oc apply -f ./llm-app/k8s-manifest.yaml&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;Note: to build a Docker image for this Python application, we executed the following commands:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="code-block"&gt;
 &lt;div class="code-block__header"&gt;
 &lt;span class="code-block__file"&gt;&lt;span class="code-block__lang"&gt;bash&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;button class="code-block__copy" type="button" aria-label="Copy code to clipboard"&gt;Copy&lt;/button&gt;
 &lt;/div&gt;
 &lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"&gt;&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash"&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="nb"&gt;cd&lt;/span&gt; workshop/cisco-ai-pods/llm-app
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;docker build --platform linux/amd64 -t ghcr.io/splunk/cisco-ai-pod-workshop-app:1.0 .
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;docker push ghcr.io/splunk/cisco-ai-pod-workshop-app:1.0&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;h2 id="test-the-llm-application"&gt;
 &lt;span class="heading-text"&gt;Test the LLM Application&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;a class="heading-anchor" href="#test-the-llm-application" aria-label="Permalink" aria-hidden="true"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Let&amp;rsquo;s ensure the application is working as expected.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Review Metrics, Traces, and Logs</title><link>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/ninja-workshops/14-cisco-ai-pods/2-workshop/11-review-traces/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/ninja-workshops/14-cisco-ai-pods/2-workshop/11-review-traces/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="view-trace-data-in-splunk-observability-cloud"&gt;
 &lt;span class="heading-text"&gt;View Trace Data in Splunk Observability Cloud&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;a class="heading-anchor" href="#view-trace-data-in-splunk-observability-cloud" aria-label="Permalink" aria-hidden="true"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In Splunk Observability Cloud, navigate to &lt;code&gt;APM&lt;/code&gt; and then select &lt;code&gt;Service Map&lt;/code&gt;.
Ensure your environment name is selected (e.g. &lt;code&gt;ai-pod-workshop-participant-1&lt;/code&gt;).&lt;br&gt;
You should see a service map that looks like the following:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;figure class="figure"&gt;
 &lt;div class="figure__inner"&gt;
 &lt;img src="../../images/ServiceMap.png" alt="Service Map" loading="lazy" decoding="async"&gt;
 &lt;/div&gt;
 
&lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Click on &lt;code&gt;Traces&lt;/code&gt; on the right-hand side menu. Then select one of the slower running
traces. It should look like the following example:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;figure class="figure"&gt;
 &lt;div class="figure__inner"&gt;
 &lt;img src="../../images/Trace.png" alt="Trace" loading="lazy" decoding="async"&gt;
 &lt;/div&gt;
 
&lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The trace shows all the interactions that our application executed to return an answer
to the users question (i.e. &amp;ldquo;How much memory does the NVIDIA H200 have?&amp;rdquo;)&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Wrap-Up</title><link>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/ninja-workshops/14-cisco-ai-pods/2-workshop/12-wrapup/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://splunk.github.io/observability-workshop/ninja-workshops/14-cisco-ai-pods/2-workshop/12-wrapup/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="wrap-up"&gt;
 &lt;span class="heading-text"&gt;Wrap-Up&lt;/span&gt;
 &lt;a class="heading-anchor" href="#wrap-up" aria-label="Permalink" aria-hidden="true"&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We hope you enjoyed this workshop, which provided hands-on experience deploying and working
with several of the technologies that are used to monitor Cisco AI PODs with
Splunk Observability Cloud. Specifically, you had the opportunity to:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Work with a RedHat OpenShift cluster with GPU-based worker nodes.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Work with the NVIDIA NIM Operator and NVIDIA GPU Operator.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Work with Large Language Models (LLMs) deployed using NVIDIA NIM to the cluster.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Deploy the OpenTelemetry Collector in the Red Hat OpenShift cluster.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Add Prometheus receivers to the collector to ingest infrastructure metrics.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Monitor the Weaviate vector database in the cluster.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Configure monitoring for Pure Storage metrics using Prometheus.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Instrument Python services that interact with Large Language Models (LLMs) with OpenTelemetry.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Understand which details which OpenTelemetry captures in the trace from applications that interact with LLMs.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>